        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The air ride suspension is the ultimate in smooth, shock and vibration-free ride with a preset
                        constant frame height.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The air springs on the air ride suspension take the place of springs, which means there is no
                        interleaf friction to overcome. Thereby, minimum road shock is transferred to the frame, cargo
                        and driver (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300201">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0300201" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300201" filename="../figg03/G0300201.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 1. AIR SUSPENSION (6X4)</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The air ride suspension adjusts to load changes automatically, providing a "low rate"
                        suspension with a light or no load condition, and a "higher rate" suspension with heavier loads.
                        The major components of the air suspension system on tandem axles are as follows.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>HEIGHT CONTROL VALVES</title>
                    <para>Two height control valves are used to control frame height. The height control valve (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300202">Figure 2</hotlnk>) is the brain of the air suspension and is sensitive
                        to height. When properly adjusted, it will provide and maintain ride height.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300202" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300202" filename="../figg03/G0300202.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 2. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.CONTROL ARM</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.SLOT</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.ADJUSTING LOCK NUT</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.LOCATING PIN</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.ADJUSTING BLOCK</callout1>
                            <callout1>6."IN" AIR SUPPLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>7."OUT" TO AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                            <callout1>8.EXHAUST</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <para>The height control valves are installed as an assembly (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300203">Figure 3</hotlnk>). The assembly is mounted over the axle at the rear
                        of vehicle frame (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300204">Figure 4</hotlnk>). Other Neway installations may utilize the forward
                        rear axle to install the leveling valve assembly. The valves have a lever arm connected to the
                        axle assembly with a vertical linkage rod. This height control valve lever is sensitive to frame
                        height thus providing automatic filling or exhausting of the air springs to keep the vehicle
                        level.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300203" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300203" filename="../figg03/G0300203.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE ASSEMBLY</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.HEIGHT CONTROL VALVES</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.LINK ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.EXHAUST</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.LOCK NUT, 1/4-20</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.AIR SUPPLY TO HEIGHT CONTROL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>7.HEIGHT CONTROL AIR DELIVERY TO AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                            <callout1>8.EQUALIZER AIR LINE</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f0300204" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300204" filename="../figg03/G0300204.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4. AIR SPRING HOUSING AND VALVES</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.AIR SUPPLY TO RT FWD AIR SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.AIR SUPPLY TO RT SIDE AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.AIR SUPPLY TO HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.AIR SUPPLY TO LT SIDE AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.REAR TABS ON TRAVERSE BEAM</callout1>
                            <callout1>7.PRESSURE PROTECTION VALVE</callout1>
                            <callout1>8.AIR SUPPLY TO LT FWD AIR SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>9.PRIMARY AIR SUPPLY FROM RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <para>The lever arm neutral position feature (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300203">Figure 3</hotlnk>
                        and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300204">Figure 4</hotlnk>) is also incorporated in the valves and serves to
                        automatically return the valves to a closed position. The height control valves are closed in
                        the neutral position.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>AIR LINES</title>
                    <para>Air is supplied to the height control valves (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300204">Figure 4</hotlnk>) from the pressure protection valve. The air line
                        connecting the two height control valves provides equal pressure to the valves. There is a
                        delivery port on each valve supplying air to the right and left air springs.
                    </para>
                    <para>Air lines between the front and rear axle air springs provide air flow transfer between axles
                        to maintain constant frame rail height and equal load distribution between the axles (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300204">Figure 4</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>CAB AIR RELEASE</title>
                    <para>Cab air release controls permit the driver to deflate the air springs from the cab when
                        hooking up to a trailer. For normal operation, the air suspension cab control switch will be in
                        the RUN position (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300205">Figure 5</hotlnk>). To dump the air from the springs, place the valve
                        in the DUMP position. The switch has a guard to prevent an unintentional air dump.
                        <emph type="bold">Do not remove the guard.</emph>
                    </para>
                    <para>An instrument panel warning light indicates when the cab control switch is in the DUMP
                        position.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300205" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300205" filename="../figg03/G0300205.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5. CAB AIR CONTROL SWITCH</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>SHOCK ABSORBERS</title>
                    <para>Each axle is controlled by a hydraulic shock absorber (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300206">Figure 6</hotlnk>) which is mounted where shock travel is greatest to
                        provide maximum control. The shock absorbers are designed so that with air springs, the best
                        possible ride stability will be obtained.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300206" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300206" filename="../figg03/G0300206.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6. SHOCK ABSORBERS</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>TORQUE RODS</title>
                    <para>Torque rods and transverse torque rods (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300207">Figure 7</hotlnk>and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300208">Figure 8</hotlnk>) are used to minimize axle windups, caused by
                        driveline torque and resulting load transfer during braking.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300207" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300207" filename="../figg03/G0300207.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7. TYPICAL TORQUE ROD INSTALLATION FORWARD REAR AXLE</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.BRACKET TORQUE ROD MOUNTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.TORQUE ROD FRONT</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.CHANNEL REINFORCEMENT TORQUE ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.BAR TORQUE ROD MOUNTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.BRACKET, TRANSVERSE TORQUE ROD MOUNTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.TRANSVERSE TORQUE ROD FRONT</callout1>
                            <callout1>7.BOLT, HEX HEAD</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f0300208" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300208" filename="../figg03/G0300208.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 8. TYPICAL TORQUE ROD INSTALLATION - REAR REAR AXLE</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.BRACKET TORQUE ROD MOUNTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.TORQUE ROD REAR</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.TRANSVERSE TORQUE ROD REAR</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.BOLT, HEX HEAD</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.CHANNEL REINFORCEMENT -TORQUE ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.BAR - TORQUE ROD MOUNTING (ONE USED WITH REINF. FRAME, TWO USED WITHOUT REINF.
                                FRAME)
                            </callout1>
                            <callout1>7.BRACKET, TRANSVERSE TORQUE ROD MOUNTING</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
            </geninfo>
